description:
Defines the official Typography System for the LexMastery Design Language.

alwaysApply: true
---

# Typography System

Typography is the primary interface of LexMastery.

Reading is the core user activity.

Typography must optimize:

Comprehension

Retention

Scanning

Accessibility

Comfort

Confidence

Never optimize typography for visual decoration.

Always optimize for readability.

---

# Typography Philosophy

LexMastery typography should feel:

Professional

Academic

Premium

Modern

Calm

Editorial

Structured

Trustworthy

The experience should resemble:

Apple Books

Medium

Notion

Kindle

Financial Times

Harvard Business Review

—not—

Social media feeds.

---

# Typography Hierarchy

Every text belongs to one category.

Display

↓

Headline

↓

Title

↓

Body

↓

Supporting

↓

Caption

↓

Label

Never invent additional hierarchy levels.

---

# Font Family

The project uses a single primary font family.

Primary Font

Inter

Fallback

System Sans Serif

Do not mix font families unless explicitly approved.

---

# Font Weights

Use only approved weights.

Regular

Medium

SemiBold

Bold

Avoid Light and Thin weights for body text.

Avoid Black and ExtraBold except for display headings.

---

# Line Height

Reading comfort is more important than density.

Body text should use generous line height.

Headings should use tighter line height.

Never compress multiline text.

---

# Letter Spacing

Use neutral tracking.

Never apply excessive letter spacing.

Avoid negative tracking except for large display text.

---

# Text Alignment

Default alignment:

Left

Never justify paragraphs.

Center alignment is reserved for:

Hero sections

Empty states

Celebration screens

Everything else remains left aligned.

---

# Paragraph Width

Never allow excessively wide reading columns.

Optimize for comfortable reading.

Break long content into sections.

Use headings frequently.

---

# Heading Rules

Headings communicate structure.

Every screen should have one primary heading.

Avoid multiple competing headlines.

---

# Body Text

Body text is the most important typography style.

It should remain:

Readable

Comfortable

Accessible

Never sacrifice readability for aesthetics.

---

# Supporting Text

Supporting text provides context.

Use reduced emphasis.

Never reduce readability.

---

# Captions

Captions communicate metadata.

Examples:

Dates

Progress

Question numbers

Sources

Time estimates

Avoid long paragraphs in captions.

---

# Labels

Labels identify UI controls.

Labels should remain concise.

Never use labels for explanatory text.

---

# Legal References

Legal citations have dedicated styling.

Examples:

Case Names

Statutes

Sections

Acts

Regulations

Citations should stand out without disrupting reading.

---

# AI Responses

AI responses prioritize readability.

Support:

Headings

Lists

Tables

Code blocks

Legal citations

Block quotes

Definitions

Examples

Warnings

AI should never produce large walls of text.

---

# Question Typography

Quiz questions require high emphasis.

Options require medium emphasis.

Explanations prioritize readability.

Correct answers should never rely solely on color.

---

# Flashcards

Front side

High emphasis

Back side

Comfortable reading

Hints

Supporting typography

---

# Progress Numbers

Scores

Percentages

Statistics

Use tabular numerals when appropriate.

Align numbers consistently.

---

# Accessibility

Support Dynamic Type.

Support large font sizes.

Never truncate important content.

Allow text to wrap naturally.

Avoid fixed-height text containers.

---

# Responsive Typography

Typography scales gracefully.

Do not create separate font systems for phones and tablets.

Use responsive scaling through typography tokens.

---

# Text Styles

Expose typography through Theme Extensions.

Example:

context.typography.displayLarge

context.typography.headlineMedium

context.typography.bodyLarge

context.typography.captionSmall

Never create TextStyle directly inside widgets.

---

# Rich Text

Prefer semantic formatting.

Avoid excessive bold text.

Avoid excessive italics.

Use emphasis sparingly.

---

# Reading Rhythm

Large blocks of text should include:

Headings

Lists

Spacing

Quotes

Examples

Dividers

Never overwhelm the user.

---

# AI Thinking Panels

AI reasoning panels use a slightly reduced emphasis than the final answer.

Reasoning should appear informative, not authoritative.

---

# Error Messages

Errors should remain calm.

Avoid alarming typography.

Use concise language.

---

# Empty States

Empty states should:

Explain

Guide

Encourage

Typography should reduce anxiety.

---

# Cursor Instructions

Whenever generating UI:

Use typography tokens only.

Never hardcode TextStyle.

Never hardcode font size.

Never hardcode font weight.

Always preserve reading comfort.

Optimize every screen for prolonged study sessions.